The '''Museum of Hoaxes''' is a [[website]] created by Alex Boese in 1997 in [[San Diego]], [[California]] as a resource for reporting and discussing [[hoax]]es and [[urban legends]], both past and present.<ref>Emery, David, [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/gate/archive/2002/12/19/aboese.DTL ''"The Bunk Stops Here: An interview with Alex Boese, curator of the Museum of Hoaxes"''], [[San Francisco Chronicle]], December 19, 2002 (URL last accessed November 1, 2006).</ref><ref>Berman, A. S., [https://www.usatoday.com/tech/2001-08-16-net-interest.htm ''"Museum-of-Hoaxes highlights online gullibility"''], [[USA Today]], August 16, 2001 (URL last accessed November 1, 2006).</ref><ref>[[Daniel Terdiman|Terdiman, Daniel]], [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C06E5D8133DF93AA15754C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all "Wry Hoaxes Enliven the World of Web Diarists"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 29, 2004 (URL last accessed May 23, 2008).</ref><ref name="ShaferKit">{{cite news |last1=Shafer |first1=Jack |title=The April Fools’ Day Defense Kit |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2007/03/april-fools-day-here-s-a-guide-to-outsmarting-the-inevitable-slew-of-media-pranks.html |accessdate=29 October 2018 |publisher=Slate |date=29 March 2007}}</ref>
In 2004, PC Magazine included the site as one of the "Top 100 Sites You Didn't Know You Couldn't Live Without,"<ref>[http://www.federatedmedia.net/authors/hoaxes ''"Museum of Hoaxes" (advertiser profile)''], [[Federated Media Publishing Inc|Federated Media Publishing]], URL last accessed November 1, 2006.</ref><ref>[https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,1895,1558713,00.asp ''"The Museum of Hoaxes"''], [[PC Magazine]], April 20, 2004 (URL last accessed November 1, 2006).</ref> and Sci Fi Weekly named it "site of the week" for the week beginning 7 February 2007.<ref>Dellamonica, A. M., [http://www.scifi.com/sfw/sites/sfw14872.html ''"Museum of Hoaxes"''], [[Sci Fi Weekly]], February 7, 2007 (URL last accessed November 17, 2007).</ref>
Boese has published two books on hoaxes: ''Museum of Hoaxes'' ([[E.P. Dutton]], 2002, {{ISBN|0-525-94678-0}}) and ''[[Hippo eats dwarf|Hippo Eats Dwarf]]: A Field Guide to Hoaxes and Other B.S.'' (Harvest Books, 2006, {{ISBN|0-15-603083-7}}). A third book by Boese, ''Elephants on Acid'' (Harvest Books, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-15-603135-6}}), focuses on unusual scientific experiments. His latest book is ''Electrified Sheep'', published by Boxtree 2011, is also about strange scientific experiments.
